Juba holds that at Cape Mossylites begins the Atlantic Ocean‚ navigable with a north-west wind along the coast of his kingdom of the Mauretanias as far as Cadiz; and his whole opinion must not be omitted at this point in the narrative. He puts forward the view that the distance from the cape in the Indian⁹ territory called in Greek the Narrow Head, and by others the sickle, in a straight course past Bumt Island to Malichas's Islands is 1500 miles, from there to the place called Scaenei 225 miles, and on from there to Sadanus Island 150 miles—- making 1875 miles to the open sea. All the rest of the authorities have held the view that the heat of the sun makes the voyage impossible; moreover actual goods conveycd for trade are exposed to the depredations of an Arabian tribe living on the islands: who are called the Ascitaeh because they make rafts of timber placed on a pair of inflated oxhides and practise piracy, using poisoned arrows.
